# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectroscopy-nmr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The major isotope of carbon, the 12C isotope, has a spin quantum number of zero, so is not magnetically active and therefore not detectable by NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] 13C, with a spin quantum number of 1/2, is less abundant (1.1%), whereas other popular nuclei are 100% abundant, e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] 13C NMR spectroscopy is much less sensitive (ca. by 4 orders of magnitude) to carbon than 1H NMR spectroscopy is to hydrogen, because of the lower abundance (1.1%) of 13C compared to 1H (>99%), and because of a lower (0.702 vs.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Stated equivalently, the gyromagnetic ratio (6.728284 107 rad T−1 s−1) is only 1/4th that of 1H.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] On the other hand, the sensitivity of 13C NMR spectroscopy benefits to some extent from nuclear Overhauser effect, which enhances signal intensity for non-quaternary 13C atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The disadvantages in "receptivity" are compensated by the high sensitivity of 13C NMR signals to the chemical environment of the nucleus, i.e. the chemical shift "dispersion" is great, covering nearly 250 ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] This dispersion reflects the fact that non-1H nuclei are strongly influenced by excited states ("paramagnetic" contribution to shielding tensor.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] This paramagnetic contribution is unrelated to paramagnetism).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] For example, most 1H NMR signals for most organic compounds are within 15 ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The chemical shift reference standard for 13C is the carbons in tetramethylsilane (TMS), whose chemical shift is set as 0.0 ppm at every temperature.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Homonuclear 13C-13C coupling is normally only observed in samples that are enriched with 13C.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The *trends* in J(1H,13C) and J(13C,13C) are similar, except that J(1H,13C are smaller owing to the modest value of the 13C nuclear magnetic moment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Values for 2J(1H,13C) are near 5 Hz and often are negative.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] As a consequence of low receptivity, 13C NMR spectroscopy suffers from complications not encountered in proton NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Many measures can be implemented to compensate for the low receptivity of this nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] For example, high field magnets with wider internal bores are capable of accepting larger sample tubes (typically 10 mm in diameter for 13C NMR versus 5 mm for 1H NMR).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Relaxation reagents allow more rapid pulsing.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] A typical relaxation agent is chromium(III) acetylacetonate.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] For a typical sample, recording a 13C NMR spectrum may require several hours, compared to 15–30 minutes for 1H NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The nuclear dipole is weaker, the difference in energy between alpha and beta states is one-quarter that of proton NMR, and the Boltzmann population difference is correspondingly less.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] One final measure to compensate for low receptivity is isotopic enrichment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Some NMR probes, called cryoprobes, offer 20x signal enhancement relative to ordinary NMR probes.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] In cryoprobes, the RF generating and receiving electronics are maintained at ~ 25K using helium gas, which greatly enhances their sensitivity.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The trade-off is that cryoprobes are costly.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Another potential complication results from the presence of large one bond J-coupling constants between carbon and hydrogen (typically from 100 to 250 Hz).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] While potentially informative, these couplings can complicate the spectra and reduce sensitivity.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] For these reasons, 13C-NMR spectra are usually recorded with proton NMR decoupling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Couplings between carbons can be ignored due to the low natural abundance of 13C.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Hence in contrast to typical proton NMR spectra, which show multiplets for each proton position, carbon NMR spectra show a single peak for each chemically non-equivalent carbon atom.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] In further contrast to 1H NMR, the intensities of the signals are often not proportional to the number of equivalent 13C atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Instead, signal intensity is strongly influenced by (and proportional to) the number of surrounding spins (typically 1H).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Integrations are more quantitative if the delay times are long, i.e. if the delay times greatly exceed relaxation times.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The most common modes of recording 13C spectra are proton-noise decoupling (also known as noise-, proton-, or broadband- decoupling), off-resonance decoupling, and gated decoupling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] These modes are meant to address the large J values for 13C - H (110–320 Hz), 13C - C - H (5–60 Hz), and 13C - C - C - H (5–25 Hz) which otherwise make completely proton coupled 13C spectra difficult to interpret.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] With proton-noise decoupling, in which most spectra are run, a noise decoupler strongly irradiates the sample with a broad (approximately 1000 Hz) range of radio frequencies covering the range (such as 100 MHz for a 23,486 gauss field) at which protons change their nuclear spin.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The rapid changes in proton spin create an effective heteronuclear decoupling, increasing carbon signal strength on account of the nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) and simplifying the spectrum so that each non-equivalent carbon produces a singlet peak.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Both the atoms, carbon and hydrogen exhibit spins and are NMR active.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The nuclear Overhauser Effect is in general, showing up when one of two different types of atoms is irradiated while the NMR spectrum of the other type is determined.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] If the absorption intensities of the observed (i.e., non-irradiated) atom change, enhancement occurs.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The effect can be either positive or negative, depending on which atom types are involved.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The relative intensities are unreliable because some carbons have a larger spin-lattice relaxation time and others have weaker NOE enhancement.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] In gated decoupling, the noise decoupler is gated on early in the free induction delay but gated off for the pulse delay.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] This largely prevents NOE enhancement, allowing the strength of individual 13C peaks to be meaningfully compared by integration, at a cost of half to two-thirds of the overall sensitivity.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] With off-resonance decoupling, the noise decoupler irradiates the sample at 1000–2000 Hz upfield or 2000–3000 Hz downfield of the proton resonance frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] This retains couplings between protons immediately adjacent to 13C atoms but most often removes the others, allowing narrow multiplets to be visualized with one extra peak per bound proton (unless bound methylene protons are non-equivalent, in which case a pair of doublets may be observed).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Signals from quaternary carbons and other carbons with no attached protons are always absent (due to the lack of attached protons).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] The polarization transfer from 1H to 13C has the secondary advantage of increasing the sensitivity over the normal 13C spectrum (which has a modest enhancement from the nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) due to the 1H decoupling).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Another useful way of determining how many protons a carbon in a molecule is bonded to is to use an **attached proton test** (APT), which distinguishes between carbon atoms with even or odd number of attached hydrogens.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Even though this technique does not distinguish fully between CHn groups, it is so easy and reliable that it is frequently employed as a first attempt to assign peaks in the spectrum and elucidate the structure.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] Additionally, signals from quaternary carbons and other carbons with no attached protons are still detectable, so in many cases an additional conventional 13C spectrum is not required, which is an advantage over DEPT.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] It is, however, sometimes possible that a CH and CH2 signal have coincidentally equivalent chemical shifts resulting in annulment in the APT spectrum due to the opposite phases.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/carbon-13-nuclear-magnetic-resonance] For this reason the conventional 13C{1H} spectrum or HSQC are occasionally also acquired.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy, the **chemical shift** is the resonant frequency of an atomic nucleus relative to a standard in a magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Often the position and number of chemical shifts are diagnostic of the structure of a molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Chemical shifts are also used to describe signals in other forms of spectroscopy such as photoemission spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Some atomic nuclei possess a magnetic moment (nuclear spin), which gives rise to different energy levels and resonance frequencies in a magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The total magnetic field experienced by a nucleus includes local magnetic fields induced by currents of electrons in the molecular orbitals (electrons have a magnetic moment themselves).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The electron distribution of the same type of nucleus (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] 1H, 13C, 15N) usually varies according to the local geometry (binding partners, bond lengths, angles between bonds, and so on), and with it the local magnetic field at each nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] This is reflected in the spin energy levels (and resonance frequencies).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The variations of nuclear magnetic resonance frequencies of the same kind of nucleus, due to variations in the electron distribution, is called the chemical shift.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The size of the chemical shift is given with respect to a reference frequency or reference sample (see also chemical shift referencing), usually a molecule with a barely distorted electron distribution.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] where *B*0 is the induction of the magnet (SI units of tesla), and $\gamma$ is the magnetogyric ratio of the nucleus — an empirically measured fundamental constant determined by the details of the structure of each nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] MRI scanners are often referred to by their field strengths *B*0 (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] "a 7 T scanner"), whereas NMR spectrometers are commonly referred to by the corresponding proton Larmor frequency (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] "a 300 MHz spectrometer", which has a *B*0 of 7 T).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] While chemical shift is referenced in order that the units are equivalent across different field strengths, the actual frequency separation in hertz scales with field strength (*B*0).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] As a result, the difference of chemical shift between two signals (ppm) represents a larger number of hertz on machines that have larger *B*0, and therefore the signals are less likely to be overlapping in the resulting spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] This increased resolution is a significant advantage for analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Higher-field machines are also favoured on account of having intrinsically higher signal arising from the Boltzmann distribution of magnetic spin states.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] where *ν*sample is the absolute resonance frequency of the sample, and *ν*ref is the absolute resonance frequency of a standard reference compound, measured in the same applied magnetic field *B*0.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Since the numerator is usually expressed in hertz, and the denominator in megahertz, δ is expressed in ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The detected frequencies (in Hz) for 1H, 13C, and 29Si nuclei are usually referenced against TMS (tetramethylsilane), TSP (trimethylsilylpropanoic acid), or DSS, which by the definition above have a chemical shift of zero if chosen as the reference.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Other standard materials are used for setting the chemical shift for other nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Although the absolute resonance frequency depends on the applied magnetic field, the chemical shift is independent of external magnetic field strength.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] On the other hand, the resolution of NMR will increase with applied magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In early proton NMR publications, the τ scale was also used, defined as τ = 10 ppm - δTMS.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Practically speaking, diverse methods may be used to reference chemical shifts in an NMR experiment, which can be subdivided into *indirect* and *direct* referencing methods.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Indirect referencing uses a channel other than the one of interest to adjust chemical shift scale correctly, i.e. the solvent signal in the deuterium (lock) channel can be used to reference the a 1H NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] **External referencing**, involving sample and reference contained separately in coaxial cylindrical tubes.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] With this procedure, the reference signal is still visible in the spectrum of interest, although the reference and the sample are physically separated by a glass wall.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Magnetic susceptibility differences between the sample and the reference phase need to be corrected theoretically, which lowers the practicality of this procedure.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] **Substitution method**: The use of separate cylindrical tubes for the sample and the reference compound, with (in principle) spectra recorded individually for each.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Similar to external referencing, this method allows referencing without sample contamination.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] If field/frequency locking via the 2H signal of the deuterated solvent is used and the solvents of reference and analyte are the same, the use of this methods is straightforward.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Problems may arise if different solvents are used for the reference compound and the sample as (just like for external referencing) magnetic susceptibility differences need to be corrected theoretically.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] If this method is used without field/frequency locking, shimming procedures between the sample and the reference need to be avoided as they change the applied magnetic field (and thereby influence the chemical shift).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] This system, however, relies on accurately determined 2H NMR chemical shifts enlisted in the spectrometer software and correctly determined Ξ values by IUPAC.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] A recent study for 19F NMR spectroscopy revealed that the use of the absolute scale and lock-based internal referencing led to errors in chemical shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] These may be negated by inclusion of calibrated reference compounds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The electrons around a nucleus will circulate in a magnetic field and create a secondary induced magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] This field opposes the applied field as stipulated by Lenz's law and atoms with higher induced fields (i.e., higher electron density) are therefore called *shielded*, relative to those with lower electron density.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Electron-donating alkyl groups, for example, lead to increased shielding whereas electron-withdrawing substituents such as nitro groups lead to *deshielding* of the nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Not only substituents cause local induced fields.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Bonding electrons can also lead to shielding and deshielding effects.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] A striking example of this is the pi bonds in benzene.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Circular current through the hyperconjugated system causes a shielding effect at the molecule's center and a deshielding effect at its edges.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Trends in chemical shift are explained based on the degree of shielding or deshielding.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Nuclei are found to resonate in a wide range to the left (or more rare to the right) of the internal standard.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Conversely a lower chemical shift is called a **diamagnetic shift**, and is **upfield** and more shielded.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In real molecules protons are surrounded by a cloud of charge due to adjacent bonds and atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In an applied magnetic field (**B**0) electrons circulate and produce an induced field (**B**i) which opposes the applied field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The effective field at the nucleus will be **B** = **B**0 − **B**i.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The nucleus is said to be experiencing a diamagnetic shielding.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Important factors influencing chemical shift are electron density, electronegativity of neighboring groups and anisotropic induced magnetic field effects.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Electron density shields a nucleus from the external field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] For example, in proton NMR the electron-poor tropylium ion has its protons downfield at 9.17 ppm, those of the electron-rich cyclooctatetraenyl anion move upfield to 6.75 ppm and its dianion even more upfield to 5.56 ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] A nucleus in the vicinity of an electronegative atom experiences reduced electron density and the nucleus is therefore deshielded.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In proton NMR of methyl halides (CH3X) the chemical shift of the methyl protons increase in the order I < Br < Cl < F from 2.16 ppm to 4.26 ppm reflecting this trend.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In carbon NMR the chemical shift of the carbon nuclei increase in the same order from around −10 ppm to 70 ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Also when the electronegative atom is removed further away the effect diminishes until it can be observed no longer.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Anisotropic induced magnetic field effects are the result of a local induced magnetic field experienced by a nucleus resulting from circulating electrons that can either be paramagnetic when it is parallel to the applied field or diamagnetic when it is opposed to it.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] It is observed in alkenes where the double bond is oriented perpendicular to the external field with pi electrons likewise circulating at right angles.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The induced magnetic field lines are parallel to the external field at the location of the alkene protons which therefore shift downfield to a 4.5 ppm to 7.5 ppm range.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The three-dimensional space where a diamagnetic shift is called the shielding zone with a cone-like shape aligned with the external field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The protons in aromatic compounds are shifted downfield even further with a signal for benzene at 7.73 ppm as a consequence of a diamagnetic ring current.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Alkyne protons by contrast resonate at high field in a 2–3 ppm range.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] For alkynes the most effective orientation is the external field in parallel with electrons circulation around the triple bond.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In this way the acetylenic protons are located in the cone-shaped shielding zone hence the upfield shift.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] 1H and 13C are not the only nuclei susceptible to NMR experiments.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In general, the associated increased signal-to-noise and resolution has driven a move towards increasingly high field strengths.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In limited cases, however, lower fields are preferred; examples are for systems in chemical exchange, where the speed of the exchange relative to the NMR experiment can cause additional and confounding linewidth broadening.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Similarly, while avoidance of second order coupling is generally preferred, this information can be useful for elucidation of chemical structures.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Using refocussing pulses placed between recording of successive points of the free induction decay, in an analogous fashion to the spin echo technique in MRI, the chemical shift evolution can be scaled to provide apparent low-field spectra on a high-field spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] In a similar fashion, it is possible to upscale the effect of J-coupling relative to the chemical shift using pulse sequences that include additional J-coupling evolution periods interspersed with conventional spin evolutions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The Knight shift (first reported in 1949) and Shoolery's rule are observed with pure metals and methylene groups, respectively.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The NMR chemical shift in its present-day meaning first appeared in journals in 1950.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] Chemical shifts with a different meaning appear in X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy as the shift in atomic core-level energy due to a specific chemical environment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] The term is also used in Mössbauer spectroscopy, where similarly to NMR it refers to a shift in peak position due to the local chemical bonding environment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/chemical-shift] As is the case for NMR the chemical shift reflects the electron density at the atomic nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The perturbation of this alignment of the nuclear spins by a weak oscillating magnetic field, usually referred to as a radio-frequency (RF) pulse.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Detection and analysis of the electromagnetic waves emitted by the nuclei of the sample as a result of this perturbation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Similarly, biochemists use NMR to identify proteins and other complex molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Besides identification, NMR spectroscopy provides detailed information about the structure, dynamics, reaction state, and chemical environment of molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most common types of NMR are proton and carbon-13 NMR spectroscopy, but it is applicable to any kind of sample that contains nuclei possessing spin.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectra are unique, well-resolved, analytically tractable and often highly predictable for small molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Different functional groups are obviously distinguishable, and identical functional groups with differing neighboring substituents still give distinguishable signals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR has largely replaced traditional wet chemistry tests such as color reagents or typical chromatography for identification.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most significant drawback of NMR spectroscopy is its poor sensitivity (compared to other analytical methods, such as mass spectrometry).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Typically 2–50 mg of a substance is required to record a decent-quality NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The NMR method is non-destructive, thus the substance may be recovered.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] To obtain high-resolution NMR spectra, solid substances are usually dissolved to make liquid solutions, although solid-state NMR spectroscopy is also possible.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The timescale of NMR is relatively long, and thus it is not suitable for observing fast phenomena, producing only an averaged spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Although large amounts of impurities do show on an NMR spectrum, better methods exist for detecting impurities, as NMR is inherently not very sensitive – though at higher frequencies, sensitivity is higher.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Correlation spectroscopy is a development of ordinary NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In two-dimensional NMR, the emission is centered around a single frequency, and correlated resonances are observed.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This allows identifying the neighboring substituents of the observed functional group, allowing unambiguous identification of the resonances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There are also more complex 3D and 4D methods and a variety of methods designed to suppress or amplify particular types of resonances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) spectroscopy, the relaxation of the resonances is observed.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] As NOE depends on the proximity of the nuclei, quantifying the NOE for each nucleus allows construction of a three-dimensional model of the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectrometers are relatively expensive; universities usually have them, but they are less common in private companies.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Between 2000 and 2015, an NMR spectrometer cost around 0.5–5 million USD.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Modern NMR spectrometers have a very strong, large and expensive liquid-helium-cooled superconducting magnet, because resolution directly depends on magnetic field strength.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Higher magnetic field also improves the sensitivity of the NMR spectroscopy, which depends on the population difference between the two nuclear levels, which increases exponentially with the magnetic field strength.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Less expensive machines using permanent magnets and lower resolution are also available, which still give sufficient performance for certain applications such as reaction monitoring and quick checking of samples.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There are even benchtop nuclear magnetic resonance spectrometers.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectra of protons (1H nuclei) can be observed even in Earth magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Low-resolution NMR produces broader peaks, which can easily overlap one another, causing issues in resolving complex structures.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The use of higher-strength magnetic fields result in a better sensitivity and higher resolution of the peaks, and it is preferred for research purposes.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Credit for the discovery of NMR goes to Isidor Isaac Rabi, who received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1944.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The Purcell group at Harvard University and the Bloch group at Stanford University independently developed NMR spectroscopy in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Edward Mills Purcell and Felix Bloch shared the 1952 Nobel Prize in Physics for their inventions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The key determinant of NMR activity in atomic nuclei is the nuclear spin quantum number (*I*).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This intrinsic quantum property, similar to an atom's "spin", characterizes the angular momentum of the nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] To be NMR-active, a nucleus must have a non-zero nuclear spin (*I* ≠ 0).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is this non-zero spin that enables nuclei to interact with external magnetic fields and show signals in NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Atoms with an odd sum of protons and neutrons exhibit half-integer values for the nuclear spin quantum number (*I* = 1/2, 3/2, 5/2, and so on).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These atoms are NMR-active because they possess non-zero nuclear spin.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Atoms with an even sum but both an odd number of protons and an odd number of neutrons exhibit integer nuclear spins (*I* = 1, 2, 3, and so on).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Conversely, atoms with an even number of both protons and neutrons have a nuclear spin quantum number of zero (*I* = 0), and therefore are not NMR-active.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR-active nuclei, particularly those with a spin quantum number of 1/2, are of great significance in NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] When placed in a magnetic field, NMR active nuclei (such as 1H or 13C) absorb electromagnetic radiation at a frequency characteristic of the isotope.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The resonant frequency, energy of the radiation absorbed, and the intensity of the signal are proportional to the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, in a 21-tesla magnetic field, hydrogen nuclei (protons) resonate at 900 MHz.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is common to refer to a 21 T magnet as a 900 MHz magnet, since hydrogen is the most common nucleus detected.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, different nuclei will resonate at different frequencies at this field strength in proportion to their nuclear magnetic moments.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Spinning the sample is usually necessary to average out diffusional motion, however, some experiments call for a stationary sample when solution movement is an important variable.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For instance, measurements of diffusion constants (*diffusion ordered spectroscopy* or DOSY) are done using a stationary sample with spinning off, and flow cells can be used for online analysis of process flows.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The vast majority of molecules in a solution are solvent molecules, and most regular solvents are hydrocarbons and so contain NMR-active hydrogen-1 nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In order to avoid having the signals from solvent hydrogen atoms overwhelm the experiment and interfere in analysis of the dissolved analyte, deuterated solvents are used where >99% of the protons are replaced with deuterium (hydrogen-2).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most widely used deuterated solvent is deuterochloroform (CDCl3), although other solvents may be used for various reasons, such as solubility of a sample, desire to control hydrogen bonding, or melting or boiling points.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The chemical shifts of a molecule change slightly between solvents, and therefore the solvent used is almost always reported with chemical shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Proton NMR spectra are often calibrated against the known solvent residual proton peak as an internal standard instead of adding tetramethylsilane (TMS), which is conventionally defined as having a chemical shift of zero.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] To detect the very small frequency shifts due to nuclear magnetic resonance, the applied magnetic field must be extremely uniform throughout the sample volume.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] High-resolution NMR spectrometers use shims to adjust the homogeneity of the magnetic field to parts per billion (ppb) in a volume of a few cubic centimeters.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In modern NMR spectrometers shimming is adjusted automatically, though in some cases the operator has to optimize the shim parameters manually to obtain the best possible resolution.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Upon excitation of the sample with a radio frequency (60–1000 MHz) pulse, a nuclear magnetic resonance response – a free induction decay (FID) – is obtained.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is a very weak signal and requires sensitive radio receivers to pick up.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A Fourier transform is carried out to extract the frequency-domain spectrum from the raw time-domain FID.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A spectrum from a single FID has a low signal-to-noise ratio, but it improves readily with averaging of repeated acquisitions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Good 1H NMR spectra can be acquired with 16 repeats, which takes only minutes.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, for elements heavier than hydrogen, the relaxation time is rather long, e.g. around 8 seconds for 13C.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Thus, acquisition of quantitative heavy-element spectra can be time-consuming, taking tens of minutes to hours.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Following the pulse, the nuclei are, on average, excited to a certain angle vs. the spectrometer magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The extent of excitation can be controlled with the pulse width, typically about 3–8 μs for the optimal 90° pulse.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The pulse width can be determined by plotting the (signed) intensity as a function of pulse width.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It follows a sine curve and, accordingly, changes sign at pulse widths corresponding to 180° and 360° pulses.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Decay times of the excitation, typically measured in seconds, depend on the effectiveness of relaxation, which is faster for lighter nuclei and in solids, slower for heavier nuclei and in solutions, and can be very long in gases.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] If the second excitation pulse is sent prematurely before the relaxation is complete, the average magnetization vector has not decayed to ground state, which affects the strength of the signal in an unpredictable manner.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In practice, the peak areas are then not proportional to the stoichiometry; only the presence, but not the amount of functional groups is possible to discern.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] An inversion recovery experiment can be done to determine the relaxation time and thus the required delay between pulses.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A 180° pulse, an adjustable delay, and a 90° pulse is transmitted.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] When the 90° pulse exactly cancels out the signal, the delay corresponds to the time needed for 90° of relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Inversion recovery is worthwhile for quantitative 13C, 2D and other time-consuming experiments.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR signals are ordinarily characterized by three variables: chemical shift, spin–spin coupling, and relaxation time.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The energy difference Δ*E* between nuclear spin states is proportional to the magnetic field (Zeeman effect). Δ*E* is also sensitive to the electronic environment of the nucleus, giving rise to what is known as the chemical shift, δ.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The simplest types of NMR graphs are plots of the different chemical shifts of the nuclei being studied in the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The value of δ is often expressed in terms of "shielding": shielded nuclei have higher Δ*E*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The range of δ values is called the dispersion.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is rather small for 1H signals, but much larger for other nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR signals are reported relative to a reference signal, usually that of TMS (tetramethylsilane).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Additionally, since the distribution of NMR signals is field-dependent, these frequencies are divided by the spectrometer frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, since we are dividing Hz by MHz, the resulting number would be too small, and thus it is multiplied by a million.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This operation therefore gives a locator number called the "chemical shift" with units of parts per million.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The chemical shift provides structural information.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The conversion of chemical shifts (and J's, see below) is called *assigning* the spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For diamagnetic organic compounds, assignments of 1H and 13C NMR spectra are extremely sophisticated because of the large databases and easy computational tools.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In general, chemical shifts for protons are highly predictable, since the shifts are primarily determined by shielding effects (electron density).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The chemical shifts for many heavier nuclei are more strongly influenced by other factors, including excited states ("paramagnetic" contribution to shielding tensor).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This paramagnetic contribution, which is unrelated to paramagnetism, not only disrupts trends in chemical shifts, which complicates assignments, but it also gives rise to very large chemical shift ranges.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For 31P NMR, the range is hundreds of ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In paramagnetic NMR spectroscopy, the samples are paramagnetic, i.e. they contain unpaired electrons.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The paramagnetism gives rise to very diverse chemical shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In 1H NMR spectroscopy, the chemical shift range can span up to thousands of ppm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Some of the most useful information for structure determination in a one-dimensional NMR spectrum comes from J-coupling, or scalar coupling (a special case of spin–spin coupling), between NMR active nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This coupling arises from the interaction of different spin states through the chemical bonds of a molecule and results in the splitting of NMR signals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For a proton, the local magnetic field is slightly different depending on whether an adjacent nucleus points towards or against the spectrometer magnetic field, which gives rise to two signals per proton instead of one.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These splitting patterns can be complex or simple and, likewise, can be straightforwardly interpretable or deceptive.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This coupling provides detailed insight into the connectivity of atoms in a molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The multiplicity of the splitting is an effect of the spins of the nuclei that are coupled and the number of such nuclei involved in the coupling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling to *n* equivalent spin-1/2 nuclei splits the signal into a *n* + 1 multiplet with intensity ratios following Pascal's triangle as described in the table.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling to additional spins leads to further splittings of each component of the multiplet, e.g. coupling to two different spin-1/2 nuclei with significantly different coupling constants leads to a *doublet of doublets* (abbreviation: dd).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] *Long-range* couplings over more than three bonds can often be observed in cyclic and aromatic compounds, leading to more complex splitting patterns.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, in the proton spectrum for ethanol, the CH3 group is split into a *triplet* with an intensity ratio of 1:2:1 by the two neighboring CH2 protons.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Similarly, the CH2 is split into a *quartet* with an intensity ratio of 1:3:3:1 by the three neighboring CH3 protons.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In principle, the two CH2 protons would also be split again into a *doublet* to form a *doublet of quartets* by the hydroxyl proton, but intermolecular exchange of the acidic hydroxyl proton often results in a loss of coupling information.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling to any spin-1/2 nuclei such as phosphorus-31 or fluorine-19 works in this fashion (although the magnitudes of the coupling constants may be very different).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] But the splitting patterns differ from those described above for nuclei with spin greater than 1/2 because the spin quantum number has more than two possible values.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For instance, coupling to deuterium (a spin-1 nucleus) splits the signal into a *1:1:1 triplet* because the spin 1 has three spin states.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Similarly, a spin-3/2 nucleus such as 35Cl splits a signal into a *1:1:1:1 quartet* and so on.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Coupling combined with the chemical shift (and the integration for protons) tells us not only about the chemical environment of the nuclei, but also the number of *neighboring* NMR active nuclei within the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In more complex spectra with multiple peaks at similar chemical shifts or in spectra of nuclei other than hydrogen, coupling is often the only way to distinguish different nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The magnitude of the coupling (the coupling constant *J*) is an effect of how strongly the nuclei are coupled to each other.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For simple cases, this is an effect of the bonding distance between the nuclei, the magnetic moment of the nuclei, and the dihedral angle between them.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The above description assumes that the coupling constant is small in comparison with the difference in NMR frequencies between the inequivalent spins.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] If the shift separation decreases (or the coupling strength increases), the multiplet intensity patterns are first distorted, and then become more complex and less easily analyzed (especially if more than two spins are involved).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Intensification of some peaks in a multiplet is achieved at the expense of the remainder, which sometimes almost disappear in the background noise, although the integrated area under the peaks remains constant.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In most high-field NMR, however, the distortions are usually modest, and the characteristic distortions (*roofing*) can in fact help to identify related peaks.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Some of these patterns can be analyzed with the method published by John Pople, though it has limited scope.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Second-order effects decrease as the frequency difference between multiplets increases, so that high-field (i.e. high-frequency) NMR spectra display less distortion than lower-frequency spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Early spectra at 60 MHz were more prone to distortion than spectra from later machines typically operating at frequencies at 200 MHz or above.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Furthermore, as in the figure to the right, J-coupling can be used to identify ortho-meta-para substitution of a ring.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Ortho coupling is the strongest at 15 Hz, Meta follows with an average of 2 Hz, and finally para coupling is usually insignificant for studies.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] More subtle effects can occur if chemically equivalent spins (i.e., nuclei related by symmetry and so having the same NMR frequency) have different coupling relationships to external spins.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Spins that are chemically equivalent but are not indistinguishable (based on their coupling relationships) are termed magnetically inequivalent.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, the 4 H sites of 1,2-dichlorobenzene divide into two chemically equivalent pairs by symmetry, but an individual member of one of the pairs has different couplings to the spins making up the other pair.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Magnetic inequivalence can lead to highly complex spectra, which can only be analyzed by computational modeling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Such effects are more common in NMR spectra of aromatic and other non-flexible systems, while conformational averaging about C−C bonds in flexible molecules tends to equalize the couplings between protons on adjacent carbons, reducing problems with magnetic inequivalence.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Correlation spectroscopy is one of several types of two-dimensional nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy or 2D-NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This type of NMR experiment is best known by its acronym, COSY.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Other types of two-dimensional NMR include J-spectroscopy, exchange spectroscopy (EXSY), Nuclear Overhauser effect spectroscopy (NOESY), total correlation spectroscopy (TOCSY), and heteronuclear correlation experiments, such as HSQC, HMQC, and HMBC.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In correlation spectroscopy, emission is centered on the peak of an individual nucleus; if its magnetic field is correlated with another nucleus by through-bond (COSY, HSQC, etc.) or through-space (NOE) coupling, a response can also be detected on the frequency of the correlated nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Two-dimensional NMR spectra provide more information about a molecule than one-dimensional NMR spectra and are especially useful in determining the structure of a molecule, particularly for molecules that are too complicated to work with using one-dimensional NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The first two-dimensional experiment, COSY, was proposed by Jean Jeener, a professor at Université Libre de Bruxelles, in 1971.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This experiment was later implemented by Walter P.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Ernst, who published their work in 1976.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A variety of physical circumstances do not allow molecules to be studied in solution, and at the same time not by other spectroscopic techniques to an atomic level, either.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In solid-phase media, such as crystals, microcrystalline powders, gels, anisotropic solutions, etc., it is in particular the dipolar coupling and chemical shift anisotropy that become dominant to the behaviour of the nuclear spin systems.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In conventional solution-state NMR spectroscopy, these additional interactions would lead to a significant broadening of spectral lines.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A variety of techniques allows establishing high-resolution conditions, that can, at least for 13C spectra, be comparable to solution-state NMR spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Two important concepts for high-resolution solid-state NMR spectroscopy are the limitation of possible molecular orientation by sample orientation, and the reduction of anisotropic nuclear magnetic interactions by sample spinning.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Of the latter approach, fast spinning around the magic angle is a very prominent method, when the system comprises spin-1/2 nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Spinning rates of about 20 kHz are used, which demands special equipment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A number of intermediate techniques, with samples of partial alignment or reduced mobility, is currently being used in NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Applications in which solid-state NMR effects occur are often related to structure investigations on membrane proteins, protein fibrils or all kinds of polymers, and chemical analysis in inorganic chemistry, but also include "exotic" applications like the plant leaves and fuel cells.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, Rahmani et al. studied the effect of pressure and temperature on the bicellar structures' self-assembly using deuterium NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Solid-state NMR is useful also for metal structure understanding in case of X-ray amorphous metal samples (like nano-size refractory metal 99Tc) .
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Recent studies have combined solid-state NMR with molecular dynamics simulations to resolve nanosecond-to-millisecond-scale motions in hydrated materials like amorphous calcium carbonate.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Much of the innovation within NMR spectroscopy has been within the field of protein NMR spectroscopy, an important technique in structural biology.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A common goal of these investigations is to obtain high resolution 3-dimensional structures of the protein, similar to what can be achieved by X-ray crystallography.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In contrast to X-ray crystallography, NMR spectroscopy is usually limited to proteins smaller than 35 kDa, although larger structures have been solved.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR spectroscopy is often the only way to obtain high resolution information on partially or wholly intrinsically unstructured proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It is now a common tool for the determination of Conformation Activity Relationships where the structure before and after interaction with, for example, a drug candidate is compared to its known biochemical activity.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Proteins are orders of magnitude larger than the small organic molecules discussed earlier in this article, but the basic NMR techniques and some NMR theory also applies.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Because of the much higher number of atoms present in a protein molecule in comparison with a small organic compound, the basic 1D spectra become crowded with overlapping signals to an extent where direct spectral analysis becomes untenable.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Therefore, multidimensional (2, 3 or 4D) experiments have been devised to deal with this problem.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The most important method used for structure determination of proteins utilizes NOE experiments to measure distances between atoms within the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Subsequently, the distances obtained are used to generate a 3D structure of the molecule by solving a distance geometry problem.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR can also be used to obtain information on the dynamics and conformational flexibility of different regions of a protein.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Nucleic acid NMR is the use of NMR spectroscopy to obtain information about the structure and dynamics of polynucleic acids, such as DNA or RNA.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] As of 2003, nearly half of all known RNA structures had been determined by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Nucleic acid and protein NMR spectroscopy are similar but differences exist.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Nucleic acids have a smaller percentage of hydrogen atoms, which are the atoms usually observed in NMR spectroscopy, and because nucleic acid double helices are stiff and roughly linear, they do not fold back on themselves to give "long-range" correlations.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The types of NMR usually done with nucleic acids are 1H or proton NMR, 13C NMR, 15N NMR, and 31P NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Parameters taken from the spectrum, mainly NOESY cross-peaks and coupling constants, can be used to determine local structural features such as glycosidic bond angles, dihedral angles (using the Karplus equation), and sugar pucker conformations.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For large-scale structure, these local parameters must be supplemented with other structural assumptions or models, because errors add up as the double helix is traversed, and unlike with proteins, the double helix does not have a compact interior and does not fold back upon itself.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR is also useful for investigating nonstandard geometries such as bent helices, non-Watson–Crick basepairing, and coaxial stacking.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It has been especially useful in probing the structure of natural RNA oligonucleotides, which tend to adopt complex conformations such as stem-loops and pseudoknots.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NMR is also useful for probing the binding of nucleic acid molecules to other molecules, such as proteins or drugs, by seeing which resonances are shifted upon binding of the other molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Carbohydrate NMR spectroscopy addresses questions on the structure and conformation of carbohydrates.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The analysis of carbohydrates by 1H NMR is challenging due to the limited variation in functional groups, which leads to 1H resonances concentrated in narrow bands of the NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In other words, there is poor spectral dispersion.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The anomeric proton resonances are segregated from the others due to fact that the anomeric carbons bear two oxygen atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For smaller carbohydrates, the dispersion of the anomeric proton resonances facilitates the use of 1D TOCSY experiments to investigate the entire spin systems of individual carbohydrate residues.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Knowledge of energy minima and rotational energy barriers of small molecules in solution can be found using NMR, e.g. looking at free ligand conformational preferences and conformational dynamics, respectively.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This can be used to guide drug design hypotheses, since experimental and calculated values are comparable.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For example, AstraZeneca uses NMR for its oncology research & development.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] One of the first scientific works devoted to the use of pressure as a variable parameter in NMR experiments was the work of J.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Jonas published in the journal Annual Review of Biophysics in 1994.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The use of high pressures in NMR spectroscopy was primarily driven by the desire to study biochemical systems, where the use of high pressure allows controlled changes in intermolecular interactions without significant perturbations.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Of course, attempts have been made to solve scientific problems using high-pressure NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, most of them were difficult to reproduce due to the problem of equipment for creating and maintaining high pressure.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In the most common types of NMR cells for realization of high-pressure NMR experiments are given.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] High-pressure NMR spectroscopy has been widely used for a variety of applications, mainly related to the characterization of the structure of protein molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, in recent years, software and design solutions have been proposed to characterize the chemical and spatial structures of small molecules in a supercritical fluid environment, using state parameters as a driving force for such changes.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The **nuclear Overhauser effect** (**NOE**) is the transfer of nuclear spin polarization from one population of spin-active nuclei (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] 1H, 13C, 15N etc.) to another via cross-relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A phenomenological definition of the NOE in nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy (NMR) is the change in the integrated intensity (positive or negative) of one NMR resonance that occurs when another is saturated by irradiation with an RF field.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The change in resonance intensity of a nucleus is a consequence of the nucleus being close in space to those directly affected by the RF perturbation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOE is particularly important in the assignment of NMR resonances, and the elucidation and confirmation of the structures or configurations of organic and biological molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The 1H two-dimensional NOE spectroscopy (NOESY) experiment and its extensions are important tools to identify stereochemistry of proteins and other biomolecules in solution, whereas in solid form crystal x-ray diffraction typically used to identify stereochemistry.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOE developed from the theoretical work of American physicist Albert Overhauser who in 1953 proposed that *nuclear* spin polarization could be enhanced by the microwave irradiation of the conduction *electrons* in certain metals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The electron-nuclear enhancement predicted by Overhauser was experimentally demonstrated in 7Li metal by T.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A general theoretical basis and experimental observation of an Overhauser effect involving only *nuclear* spins in the HF molecule was published by Ionel Solomon in 1955.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Another early experimental observation of the NOE was used by Kaiser in 1963 to show how the NOE may be used to determine the relative signs of scalar coupling constants, and to assign spectral lines in NMR spectra to transitions between energy levels.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this study, the resonance of one population of protons (1H) in an organic molecule was enhanced when a second distinct population of protons in the same organic molecule was saturated by RF irradiation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The application of the NOE was used by Anet and Bourn in 1965 to confirm the assignments of the NMR resonances for β,β-dimethylacrylic acid and dimethyl formamide, thereby showing that conformation and configuration information about organic molecules in solution can be obtained.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Bell and Saunders reported direct correlation between NOE enhancements and internuclear distances in 1970 while quantitative measurements of internuclear distances in molecules with three or more spins was reported by Schirmer et al.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Ernst was awarded the 1991 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for developing Fourier transform and two-dimensional NMR spectroscopy, which was soon adapted to the measurement of the NOE, particularly in large biological molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Professor Anil Kumar was the first to apply the two-dimensional Nuclear Overhauser Effect (2D-NOE now known as NOESY) experiment to a biomolecule, which opened the field for the determination of three-dimensional structures of biomolecules in solution by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOE and nuclear spin-lattice relaxation are closely related phenomena.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For a single spin-1⁄2 nucleus in a magnetic field there are two energy levels that are often labeled α and β, which correspond to the two possible spin quantum states, +1⁄2 and -1⁄2, respectively.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] At thermal equilibrium, the population of the two energy levels is determined by the Boltzmann distribution with spin populations given by *P*α and *P*β.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] If the spin populations are perturbed by an appropriate RF field at the transition energy frequency, the spin populations return to thermal equilibrium by a process called *spin-lattice relaxation*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The rate of transitions from α to β is proportional to the population of state α, *P*α, and is a first order process with rate constant *W*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The condition where the spin populations are equalized by continuous RF irradiation (*P*α = *P*β) is called *saturation* and the resonance disappears since transition probabilities depend on the population difference between the energy levels.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In the simplest case where the NOE is relevant, the resonances of two spin-1⁄2 nuclei, I and S, are chemically shifted but not J-coupled.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The energy diagram for such a system has four energy levels that depend on the spin-states of I and S corresponding to αα, αβ, βα, and ββ, respectively.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The *W'*s are the probabilities per unit time that a transition will occur between the four energy levels, or in other terms the rate at which the corresponding spin flips occur.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] There are two single quantum transitions, *W*1I, corresponding to αα ➞ βα and αβ ➞ ββ; *W*1S, corresponding to αα ➞ αβ and βα ➞ ββ; a zero quantum transition, *W*0, corresponding to βα ➞ αβ, and a double quantum transition corresponding to αα ➞ ββ.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] While rf irradiation can only induce single-quantum transitions (due to so-called quantum mechanical selection rules) giving rise to observable spectral lines, dipolar relaxation may take place through any of the pathways.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The dipolar mechanism is the only common relaxation mechanism that can cause transitions in which more than one spin flips.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Specifically, the dipolar relaxation mechanism gives rise to transitions between the αα and ββ states (*W*2) and between the αβ and the βα states (*W*0).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where $M_{0I}$ is the magnetization (resonance intensity) of nucleus I at thermal equilibrium.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] $\rho _{I}$ is the total longitudinal dipolar relaxation rate ( $1/T_{1}$ ) of spin *I* due to the presence of spin *s*, $\sigma _{IS}$ is referred to as the *cross-relaxation* rate, and $\gamma _{I}$ and $\gamma _{S}$ are the magnetogyric ratios characteristic of the I and S nuclei, respectively.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Saturation of the degenerate *W*1S transitions disturbs the equilibrium populations so that *P*αα = *P*αβ and *P*βα = *P*ββ.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This means that if only the single quantum transitions were active as relaxation pathways, saturating the S resonance would not affect the intensity of the I resonance.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore to observe an NOE on the resonance intensity of I, the contribution of $W_{0}$ and $W_{2}$ must be important.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] These pathways, known as *cross-relaxation* pathways, only make a significant contribution to the spin-lattice relaxation when the relaxation is dominated by dipole-dipole or scalar coupling interactions, but the scalar interaction is rarely important and is assumed to be negligible.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Whether the NOE is positive or negative depends sensitively on the degree of rotational molecular motion.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The three dipolar relaxation pathways contribute to differing extents to the spin-lattice relaxation depending a number of factors.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A key one is that the balance between ω2, ω1 and ω0 depends crucially on molecular rotational correlation time, $\tau _{c}$ , the time it takes a molecule to rotate one radian.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where r is the distance separating two spin-1⁄2 nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For relaxation to occur, the frequency of molecular tumbling must match the Larmor frequency of the nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In mobile solvents, molecular tumbling motion is much faster than $\omega$ .
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The so-called extreme-narrowing limit where $\omega \tau _{c}\ll 1$ ).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Under these conditions the double-quantum relaxation W2 is more effective than W1 or W0, because τc and 2ω0 match better than τc and ω1.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] When ω2 is the dominant relaxation process, a positive NOE results.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This expression shows that for the homonuclear case where *I* = *S*, most notably for 1*H* NMR, the maximum NOE that can be observed is 1\2 irrespective of the proximity of the nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In the heteronuclear case where *I* ≠ *S*, the maximum NOE is given by 1\2 (*γ*S/*γ*I), which, when observing heteronuclei under conditions of broadband proton decoupling, can produce major sensitivity improvements.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The most important example in organic chemistry is observation of 13C while decoupling 1H, which also saturates the 1J resonances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The value of *γ*S/*γ*I is close to 4, which gives a maximum NOE enhancement of 200% yielding resonances 3 times as strong as they would be without NOE.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In many cases, carbon atoms have an attached proton, which causes the relaxation to be dominated by dipolar relaxation and the NOE to be near maximum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For non-protonated carbon atoms the NOE enhancement is small while for carbons that relax by relaxation mechanisms by other than dipole-dipole interactions the NOE enhancement can be significantly reduced.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This is one motivation for using deuteriated solvents (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Since deuterium relaxes by the quadrupolar mechanism, there are no cross-relaxation pathways and NOE is non-existent.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Another important case is 15N, an example where the value of its magnetogyric ratio is negative.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Often 15N resonances are reduced or the NOE may actually null out the resonance when 1H nuclei are decoupled.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] It is usually advantageous to take such spectra with pulse techniques that involve polarization transfer from protons to the 15N to minimize the negative NOE.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For example, NOE enhancements can be used to confirm NMR resonance assignments, distinguish between structural isomers, identify aromatic ring substitution patterns and aliphatic substituent configurations, and determine conformational preferences.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The inter-atomic distances derived from the observed NOE can often help to confirm the three-dimensional structure of a molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this application, the NOE differs from the application of J-coupling in that the NOE occurs through space, not through chemical bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Thus, atoms that are in close spatial proximity to each other can give an NOE regardless of how many chemical bonds separate them, whereas spin coupling is observed only when the atoms are connected by 1–3 chemical bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] However, the relation *η*IS(max)=1⁄2 obscures how the NOE is related to internuclear distances because it applies only for the idealized case where the relaxation is 100% dominated by dipole-dipole interactions between two nuclei I and S.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In practice, the value of ρI contains contributions from other competing mechanisms, which serve only to reduce the influence of *W*0 and *W*2 by increasing *W*1.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Sometimes, for example, relaxation due to electron-nuclear interactions with dissolved oxygen or paramagnetic metal ion impurities in the solvent can prohibit the observation of weak NOE enhancements.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where ρ⋇ is the additional contribution to the total relaxation rate from relaxation mechanisms not involving cross relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Thus, the two-spin steady-state NOE depends on internuclear distance only when there is a contribution from external relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Bell and Saunders showed that following strict assumptions ρ⋇/τc is nearly constant for similar molecules in the extreme narrowing limit.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore, taking ratios of steady-state NOE values can give relative values for the internuclear distance *r*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] While the steady-state experiment is useful in many cases, it can only provide information on relative internuclear distances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] On the other hand, the initial *rate* at which the NOE grows is proportional to *r*IS−6, which provides other more sophisticated alternatives for obtaining structural information via transient experiments such as 2D-NOESY.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The motivations for using two-dimensional NMR for measuring NOEs are similar as for other 2-D methods.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The maximum resolution is improved by spreading the affected resonances over two dimensions, therefore more peaks are resolved, larger molecules can be observed and more NOEs can be observed in a single measurement.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] More importantly, when the molecular motion is in the intermediate or slow motional regimes when the NOE is either zero or negative, the steady-state NOE experiment fails to give results that can be related to internuclear distances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Nuclear Overhauser Effect Spectroscopy (NOESY) is a 2D NMR spectroscopic method used to identify nuclear spins undergoing cross-relaxation and to measure their cross-relaxation rates.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Since 1H dipole-dipole couplings provide the primary means of cross-relaxation for organic molecules in solution, spins undergoing cross-relaxation are those close to one another in space.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore, the cross peaks of a NOESY spectrum indicate which protons are close to each other in space.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this respect, the NOESY experiment differs from the COSY experiment that relies on J-coupling to provide spin-spin correlation, and whose cross peaks indicate which 1H's are close to which other 1H's through the chemical bonds of the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The basic NOESY sequence consists of three 90° pulses.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The first pulse creates transverse spin magnetization.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The spins precess during the evolution time t1, which is incremented during the course of the 2D experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The second pulse produces longitudinal magnetization equal to the transverse magnetization component orthogonal to the pulse direction.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Thus, the idea is to produce an initial condition for the mixing period τm.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] During the NOE mixing time, magnetization transfer via cross-relaxation can take place.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For the basic NOESY experiment, τm is kept constant throughout the 2D experiment, but chosen for the optimum cross-relaxation rate and build-up of the NOE.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The third pulse creates transverse magnetization from the remaining longitudinal magnetization.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Data acquisition begins immediately following the third pulse and the transverse magnetization is observed as a function of the pulse delay time t2.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOESY spectrum is generated by a 2D Fourier transform with respect to t1 and t2.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A series of experiments are carried out with increasing mixing times, and the increase in NOE enhancement is followed.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The closest protons show the most rapid build-up rates of the NOE.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Inter-proton distances can be determined from unambiguously assigned, well-resolved, high signal-to-noise NOESY spectra by analysis of cross peak intensities.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] These may be obtained by volume integration and can be converted into estimates of interproton distances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where c can be determined based on measurements of known fixed distances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The range of distances can be reported based on known distances and volumes in the spectrum, which gives a mean c and a standard deviation $c_{SD}$ , a measurement of multiple regions in the NOESY spectrum showing no peaks, *i.e.* noise $V_{\rm {err}}$ , and a measurement error $m_{v}$ .
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The parameter x is set so that all known distances are within the error bounds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Such fixed distances depend on the system studied.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For example, locked nucleic acids have many atoms whose distance varies very little in the sugar, which allows estimation of the glycosidic torsion angles, which allowed NMR to benchmark LNA molecular dynamics predictions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] RNAs, however, have sugars that are much more conformationally flexible, and require wider estimations of low and high bounds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In protein structural characterization, NOEs are used to create constraints on intramolecular distances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this method, each proton pair is considered in isolation and NOESY cross peak intensities are compared with a reference cross peak from a proton pair of fixed distance, such as a geminal methylene proton pair or aromatic ring protons.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This simple approach is reasonably insensitive to the effects of spin diffusion or non-uniform correlation times and can usually lead to definition of the global fold of the protein, provided a sufficiently large number of NOEs have been identified.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] NOESY cross peaks can be classified as strong, medium or weak and can be translated into upper distance restraints of around 2.5, 3.5 and 5.0 Å, respectively.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Such constraints can then be used in molecular mechanics optimizations to provide a picture of the solution state conformation of the protein.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Full structure determination relies on a variety of NMR experiments and optimization methods utilizing both chemical shift and NOESY constraints.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] NOESY is the determination of the relative orientations of atoms in a molecule, for example a protein or other large biological molecule, producing a three-dimensional structure.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] HOESY is NOESY cross-correlation between atoms of different elements.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] ROESY involves spin-locking the magnetization to prevent it from going to zero, applied for molecules for which regular NOESY is not applicable.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] TRNOE measures the NOE between two different molecules interacting in the same solution, as in a ligand binding to a protein.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In a DPFGSE-NOE experiment, a transient experiment that allows for suppression of strong signals and thus detection of very small NOEs.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The figure (top) displays how Nuclear Overhauser Effect Spectroscopy can elucidate the structure of a switchable compound.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this example, the proton designated as {H} shows two different sets of NOEs depending on the isomerization state (*cis* or *trans*) of the switchable azo groups.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In the *trans* state proton {H} is far from the phenyl group showing blue coloured NOEs; while the *cis* state holds proton {H} in the vicinity of the phenyl group resulting in the emergence of new NOEs (show in red).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Another example (bottom) where application where the NOE is useful to assign resonances and determine configuration is polysaccharides.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For instance, complex glucans possess a multitude of overlapping signals, especially in a proton spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore, it is advantageous to utilize 2D NMR experiments including NOESY for the assignment of signals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In quantum mechanics, **angular momentum coupling** is the procedure of constructing eigenstates of total angular momentum out of eigenstates of separate angular momenta.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] For instance, the orbit and spin of a single particle can interact through spin–orbit interaction, in which case the complete physical picture must include spin–orbit coupling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Or two charged particles, each with a well-defined angular momentum, may interact by Coulomb forces, in which case coupling of the two one-particle angular momenta to a total angular momentum is a useful step in the solution of the two-particle Schrödinger equation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In both cases the separate angular momenta are no longer constants of motion, but the sum of the two angular momenta usually still is.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Angular momentum coupling in atoms is of importance in atomic spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Angular momentum coupling of electron spins is of importance in quantum chemistry.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Also in the nuclear shell model angular momentum coupling is ubiquitous.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In astronomy, **spin–orbit coupling** reflects the general law of conservation of angular momentum, which holds for celestial systems as well.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In simple cases, the direction of the angular momentum vector is neglected, and the spin–orbit coupling is the ratio between the frequency with which a planet or other celestial body spins about its own axis to that with which it orbits another body.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] This is more commonly known as orbital resonance.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Often, the underlying physical effects are tidal forces.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Conservation of angular momentum is the principle that the total angular momentum of a system has a constant magnitude and direction if the system is subjected to no external torque.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The system moves (in quantum mechanical sense) in isotropic space.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In both cases the angular momentum operator commutes with the Hamiltonian of the system.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] By Heisenberg's uncertainty relation this means that the angular momentum and the energy (eigenvalue of the Hamiltonian) can be measured at the same time.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] An example of the first situation is an atom whose electrons only experience the Coulomb force of its atomic nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] If we ignore the electron–electron interaction (and other small interactions such as spin–orbit coupling), the *orbital angular momentum* l of each electron commutes with the total Hamiltonian.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In this model the atomic Hamiltonian is a sum of kinetic energies of the electrons and the spherically symmetric electron–nucleus interactions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The individual electron angular momenta li commute with this Hamiltonian.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] That is, they are conserved properties of this approximate model of the atom.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] An example of the second situation is a rigid rotor moving in field-free space.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] A rigid rotor has a well-defined, time-independent, angular momentum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] These two situations originate in classical mechanics.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The third kind of conserved angular momentum, associated with spin, does not have a classical counterpart.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] However, all rules of angular momentum coupling apply to spin as well.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In general the conservation of angular momentum implies full rotational symmetry (described by the groups SO(3) and SU(2)) and, conversely, spherical symmetry implies conservation of angular momentum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] If two or more physical systems have conserved angular momenta, it can be useful to combine these momenta to a total angular momentum of the combined system—a conserved property of the total system.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The building of eigenstates of the total conserved angular momentum from the angular momentum eigenstates of the individual subsystems is referred to as *angular momentum coupling*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Application of angular momentum coupling is useful when there is an interaction between subsystems that, without interaction, would have conserved angular momentum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] By the very interaction the spherical symmetry of the subsystems is broken, but the angular momentum of the total system remains a constant of motion.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Use of the latter fact is helpful in the solution of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] As an example we consider two electrons, in an atom (say the helium atom) labeled with i = 1 and 2.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] If there is no electron–electron interaction, but only electron–nucleus interaction, then the two electrons can be rotated around the nucleus independently of each other; nothing happens to their energy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The expectation values of both operators, **l**1 and **l**2, are conserved.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] However, if we switch on the electron–electron interaction that depends on the distance d(1,2) between the electrons, then only a simultaneous and equal rotation of the two electrons will leave d(1,2) invariant.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In such a case the expectation value of neither **l**1 nor **l**2 is a constant of motion in general, but the expectation value of the total orbital angular momentum operator **L** = **l**1 + **l**2 is.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Given the eigenstates of **l**1 and **l**2, the construction of eigenstates of **L** (which still is conserved) is the *coupling of the angular momenta of electrons* 1 *and* 2.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The total orbital angular momentum quantum number L is restricted to integer values and must satisfy the triangular condition that $|l_{1}-l_{2}|\leq L\leq l_{1}+l_{2}$ , such that the three nonnegative integer values could correspond to the three sides of a triangle.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In quantum mechanics, coupling also exists between angular momenta belonging to different Hilbert spaces of a single object, e.g. its spin and its orbital angular momentum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] If the spin has half-integer values, such as ⁠1/2⁠ for an electron, then the total (orbital plus spin) angular momentum will also be restricted to half-integer values.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Reiterating slightly differently the above: one expands the quantum states of composed systems (i.e. made of subunits like two hydrogen atoms or two electrons) in basis sets which are made of tensor products of quantum states which in turn describe the subsystems individually.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] We assume that the states of the subsystems can be chosen as eigenstates of their angular momentum operators (and of their component along any arbitrary z axis).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The subsystems are therefore correctly described by a pair of ℓ, m quantum numbers (see angular momentum for details).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] When there is interaction among the subsystems, the total Hamiltonian contains terms that do not commute with the angular operators acting on the subsystems only.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] However, these terms *do* commute with the *total* angular momentum operator.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Sometimes one refers to the non-commuting interaction terms in the Hamiltonian as *angular momentum coupling terms*, because they necessitate the angular momentum coupling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The behavior of atoms and smaller particles is well described by the theory of quantum mechanics, in which each particle has an intrinsic angular momentum called spin and specific configurations (of e.g. electrons in an atom) are described by a set of quantum numbers.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Collections of particles also have angular momenta and corresponding quantum numbers, and under different circumstances the angular momenta of the parts couple in different ways to form the angular momentum of the whole.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Angular momentum coupling is a category including some of the ways that subatomic particles can interact with each other.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In atomic physics, spin–orbit coupling, also known as **spin-pairing**, describes a weak magnetic interaction, or coupling, of the particle spin and the orbital motion of this particle, e.g. the electron spin and its motion around an atomic nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] One of its effects is to separate the energy of internal states of the atom, e.g. spin-aligned and spin-antialigned that would otherwise be identical in energy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] This interaction is responsible for many of the details of atomic structure.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In solid-state physics, the spin coupling with the orbital motion can lead to splitting of energy bands due to Dresselhaus or Rashba effects.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In the macroscopic world of orbital mechanics, the term *spin–orbit coupling* is sometimes used in the same sense as spin–orbit resonance.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In light atoms (generally *Z* ≤ 30), electron spins **s***i* interact among themselves so they combine to form a total spin angular momentum **S**.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The same happens with orbital angular momenta **ℓ***i*, forming a total orbital angular momentum **L**.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The interaction between the quantum numbers **L** and **S** is called **Russell–Saunders coupling** (after Henry Norris Russell and Frederick Saunders) or **LS coupling**.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] This is an approximation which is good as long as any external magnetic fields are weak.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In larger magnetic fields, these two momenta decouple, giving rise to a different splitting pattern in the energy levels (the Paschen–Back effect), and the size of LS coupling term becomes small.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] For an extensive example on how LS-coupling is practically applied, see the article on term symbols.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In heavier atoms the situation is different.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In atoms with bigger nuclear charges, spin–orbit interactions are frequently as large as or larger than spin–spin interactions or orbit–orbit interactions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In this situation, each orbital angular momentum **ℓ***i* tends to combine with the corresponding individual spin angular momentum **s***i*, originating an individual total angular momentum **j***i*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] This description, facilitating calculation of this kind of interaction, is known as *jj coupling*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Term symbols are used to represent the states and spectral transitions of atoms, they are found from coupling of angular momenta mentioned above.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] When the state of an atom has been specified with a term symbol, the allowed transitions can be found through selection rules by considering which transitions would conserve angular momentum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] A photon has spin 1, and when there is a transition with emission or absorption of a photon the atom will need to change state to conserve angular momentum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The expression "term symbol" is derived from the "term series" associated with the Rydberg states of an atom and their energy levels.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In the Rydberg formula the frequency or wave number of the light emitted by a hydrogen-like atom is proportional to the difference between the two terms of a transition.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The series known to early spectroscopy were designated *sharp*, *principal*, *diffuse*, and *fundamental* and consequently the letters S, P, D, and F were used to represent the orbital angular momentum states of an atom.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In very heavy atoms, relativistic shifting of the energies of the electron energy levels accentuates spin–orbit coupling effect.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Thus, for example, uranium molecular orbital diagrams must directly incorporate relativistic symbols when considering interactions with other atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In atomic nuclei, the spin–orbit interaction is much stronger than for atomic electrons, and is incorporated directly into the nuclear shell model.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] In addition, unlike atomic–electron term symbols, the lowest energy state is not L − S, but rather, ℓ + s.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] All nuclear levels whose ℓ value (orbital angular momentum) is greater than zero are thus split in the shell model to create states designated by ℓ + s and ℓ − s.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Due to the nature of the shell model, which assumes an average potential rather than a central Coulombic potential, the nucleons that go into the ℓ + s and ℓ − s nuclear states are considered degenerate within each orbital (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] The 2p⁠3/2⁠ contains four nucleons, all of the same energy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/spin-spin-coupling] Higher in energy is the 2p⁠1/2⁠ which contains two equal-energy nucleons).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] 2D NMR encompasses a variety of experiments, including **COSY** (Correlation Spectroscopy), **TOCSY** (Total Correlation Spectroscopy), **NOESY** (Nuclear Overhauser Effect Spectroscopy), and **HSQC** (Heteronuclear Single Quantum Coherence).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] By resolving signals that would typically overlap in the 1D NMR spectra of complex molecules, 2D NMR enhances the clarity of structural information.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] 2D NMR can provide detailed information about the chemical structure and the three-dimensional arrangement of molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The first two-dimensional experiment, COSY, was proposed by Jean Jeener, a professor at the Université Libre de Bruxelles, in 1971.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each experiment consists of a sequence of radio frequency (RF) pulses with delay periods in between them.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The timing, frequencies, and intensities of these pulses distinguish different NMR experiments from one another.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The two dimensions of a two-dimensional NMR experiment are two frequency axes representing a chemical shift.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each frequency axis is associated with one of the two time variables, which are the length of the evolution period (the *evolution time*) and the time elapsed during the detection period (the *detection time*).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] They are each converted from a time series to a frequency series through a two-dimensional Fourier transform, one in the time domain and based on the signals from each different t1 experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A single two-dimensional experiment is generated as a series of one-dimensional experiments, with a different specific evolution time in successive experiments, with the entire duration of the detection period recorded in each experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The end result is a plot showing an intensity value for each pair of frequency variables.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The intensities of the peaks in the spectrum can be represented using a third dimension.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] More commonly, intensity is indicated using contour lines or different colors.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In these methods, magnetization transfer occurs between nuclei of the same type, through J-coupling of nuclei connected by up to a few bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The first and most popular two-dimension NMR experiment is the homonuclear correlation spectroscopy (COSY) sequence, which is used to identify spins which are coupled to each other.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It consists of a single RF pulse (p1) followed by the specific evolution time (t1) followed by a second pulse (p2) followed by a measurement period (t2).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The Correlation Spectroscopy experiment operates by correlating nuclei coupled to each other through scalar coupling, also known as J-coupling.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This coupling is the interaction between nuclear spins connected by bonds, typically observed between nuclei that are 2-3 bonds apart (e.g., vicinal protons).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] By detecting these interactions, COSY provides vital information about the connectivity between atoms within a molecule, making it a crucial tool for structural elucidation in organic chemistry.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The COSY experiment generates a two-dimensional spectrum with chemical shifts along the x-axis (horizontal) and y-axis (vertical) and involves several key steps.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] First, the sample is excited using a series of radiofrequency (RF) pulses, bringing the nuclear spins into a higher energy state.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] After the first RF pulse, the system evolves freely for a period called t1, during which the spins precess at frequencies corresponding to their chemical shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The correlation between nuclei is achieved by incrementally varying the evolution time (t1) to capture indirect interactions.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This series of experiments, each with a different value of t1, allows for the detection of chemical shifts from nuclei that may not be observed directly in a one-dimensional spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] As t1 is incremented, cross-peaks are produced in the resulting 2D spectrum, representing interactions like coupling or spatial proximity between nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This approach helps map out atomic connections, providing deeper insight into molecular structure and aiding in the interpretation of complex systems.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Cross peaks result from a phenomenon called magnetization transfer, and their presence indicates that two nuclei are coupled which have the two different chemical shifts that make up the cross peak's coordinates.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each coupling gives two symmetrical cross peaks above and below the diagonal.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] That is, a cross-peak occurs when there is a correlation between the signals of the spectrum along each of the two axes at these values.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] An easy visual way to determine which couplings a cross peak represents is to find the diagonal peak which is directly above or below the cross peak, and the other diagonal peak which is directly to the left or right of the cross peak.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The nuclei represented by those two diagonal peaks are coupled.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Next, a second RF pulse is applied to allow magnetization to transfer between coupled nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The resulting signal is recorded continuously during a detection period ( t2) after the second RF pulse.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The data are then processed through Fourier transformation along both the t1 and t2 axes, creating a 2D spectrum with peaks plotted along the diagonal and off-diagonal.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] When interpreting the COSY spectrum, diagonal peaks correspond to the 1D chemical shifts of individual nuclei, similar to the standard peaks in a 1D NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The key feature of a COSY spectrum is the presence of cross-peaks as shown in Figure 1, indicating coupling between pairs of nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These cross-peaks provide crucial information about the connectivity within a molecule, showing that the two nuclei are connected by a small number of bonds, usually two or three bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] COSY is especially useful when dealing with complex molecules such as natural products, peptides, and proteins, where understanding the connectivity of different nuclei through bonds is crucial.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] While 1D NMR is more straightforward and ideal for identifying basic structural features, COSY enhances the capabilities of NMR by providing deeper insights into molecular connectivity.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The two-dimensional spectrum that results from the COSY experiment shows the frequencies for a single isotope, most commonly hydrogen (1H) along both axes.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] COSY-90 is the most common COSY experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In COSY-90, the p1 pulse tilts the nuclear spin by 90°.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Another member of the COSY family is **COSY-45**.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In COSY-45 a 45° pulse is used instead of a 90° pulse for the second pulse, p2.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The advantage of a COSY-45 is that the diagonal-peaks are less pronounced, making it simpler to match cross-peaks near the diagonal in a large molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Additionally, the relative signs of the coupling constants (see J-coupling#Magnitude of J-coupling) can be elucidated from a COSY-45 spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Overall, the COSY-45 offers a cleaner spectrum while the COSY-90 is more sensitive.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Another related COSY technique is double quantum filtered (DQF) COSY.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] DQF COSY uses a coherence selection method such as phase cycling or pulsed field gradients, which cause only signals from double-quantum coherences to give an observable signal.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This has the effect of decreasing the intensity of the diagonal peaks and changing their lineshape from a broad "dispersion" lineshape to a sharper "absorption" lineshape.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It also eliminates diagonal peaks from uncoupled nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These all have the advantage that they give a cleaner spectrum in which the diagonal peaks are prevented from obscuring the cross peaks, which are weaker in a regular COSY spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The TOCSY experiment is similar to the COSY experiment, in that cross peaks of coupled protons are observed.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, cross peaks are observed not only for nuclei which are directly coupled, but also between nuclei which are connected by a chain of couplings.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This makes it useful for identifying the larger interconnected networks of spin couplings.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This ability is achieved by inserting a repetitive series of pulses which cause *isotropic mixing* during the mixing period.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Longer isotropic mixing times cause the polarization to spread out through an increasing number of bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In the case of oligosaccharides, each sugar residue is an isolated spin system, so it is possible to differentiate all the protons of a specific sugar residue.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A 1D version of TOCSY is also available, and by irradiating a single proton the rest of the spin system can be revealed.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Recent advances in this technique include the 1D-CSSF (chemical shift selective filter) TOCSY experiment, which produces higher quality spectra and allows coupling constants to be reliably extracted and used to help determine stereochemistry.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] TOCSY is sometimes called "homonuclear Hartmann–Hahn spectroscopy" (HOHAHA).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] INADEQUATE is a method often used to find 13C couplings between adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Because the natural abundance of 13C is only about 1%, only about 0.01% of molecules being studied will have the two nearby 13C atoms needed for a signal in this experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, correlation selection methods are used (similarly to DQF COSY) to prevent signals from single 13C atoms, so that the double 13C signals can be easily resolved.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each coupled pair of nuclei gives a pair of peaks on the INADEQUATE spectrum which both have the same vertical coordinate, which is the sum of the chemical shifts of the nuclei; the horizontal coordinate of each peak is the chemical shift for each of the nuclei separately.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Heteronuclear correlation spectroscopy gives signal based upon coupling between nuclei of two different types.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Often the two nuclei are protons and another nucleus (called a "heteronucleus").
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For historical reasons, experiments which record the proton rather than the heteronucleus spectrum during the detection period are called "inverse" experiments.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This is because the low natural abundance of most heteronuclei would result in the proton spectrum being overwhelmed with signals from molecules with no active heteronuclei, making it useless for observing the desired, coupled signals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] With the advent of techniques for suppressing these undesired signals, inverse correlation experiments such as HSQC, HMQC, and HMBC are actually much more common today.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] "Normal" heteronuclear correlation spectroscopy, in which the heteronucleus spectrum is recorded, is known as HETCOR.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Heteronuclear Single Quantum Coherence (HSQC) is a 2D NMR technique utilized for the detection of interactions between different types of nuclei which are separated by one bond, particularly a proton (1H) and a heteronucleus such as carbon (13C) or nitrogen (15N).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This method gives one peak per pair of coupled nuclei, whose two coordinates are the chemical shifts of the two coupled atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This method plays a role in structural elucidation, particularly in analyzing organic compounds, natural products, and biomolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] HSQC is designed to detect one-bond correlations between protons and heteronuclear atoms, providing insight into the connectivity of hydrogen and heteronuclear atoms through the transfer of magnetization.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The HSQC experiment involves a series of steps to generate a two-dimensional NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Initially, the sample is excited using radiofrequency (RF) pulses, bringing the nuclear spins into an excited state and preparing them for magnetization transfer.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Magnetization is then transferred from the proton to the heteronucleus through a one-bond scalar coupling (J-coupling), ensuring that only directly bonded nuclei participate in the transfer.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Subsequently, the system evolves during a period called t1, and the magnetization is transferred back from the heteronuclear to the proton.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The final signal is detected, encoding both the proton and the heteronuclear information, and a Fourier transformation is performed to create a 2D spectrum correlating the proton and heteronuclear chemical shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] HSQC works by transferring magnetization from the *I* nucleus (usually the proton) to the *S* nucleus (usually the heteroatom) using the INEPT pulse sequence; this first step is done because the proton has a greater equilibrium magnetization and thus this step creates a stronger signal.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The magnetization then evolves and then is transferred back to the *I* nucleus for observation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] An extra spin echo step can then optionally be used to decouple the signal, simplifying the spectrum by collapsing multiplets to a single peak.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The undesired uncoupled signals are removed by running the experiment twice with the phase of one specific pulse reversed; this reverses the signs of the desired but not the undesired peaks, so subtracting the two spectra will give only the desired peaks.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Interpretation of the HSQC spectrum is based on the observation of cross-peaks, which indicates the direct bonding between protons and carbons or nitrogens.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Heteronuclear multiple-quantum correlation spectroscopy (HMQC) gives an identical spectrum as HSQC, but using a different method.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The two methods give similar quality results for small to medium-sized molecules, but HSQC is considered to be superior for larger molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] HMBC detects heteronuclear correlations over longer ranges of about 2–4 bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The difficulty of detecting multiple-bond correlations is that the HSQC and HMQC sequences contain a specific delay time between pulses which allows detection only of a range around a specific coupling constant.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This is not a problem for the single-bond methods since the coupling constants tend to lie in a narrow range, but multiple-bond coupling constants cover a much wider range and cannot all be captured in a single HSQC or HMQC experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In HMBC, this difficulty is overcome by omitting one of these delays from an HMQC sequence.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This increases the range of coupling constants that can be detected, and also reduces signal loss from relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The cost is that this eliminates the possibility of decoupling the spectrum, and introduces phase distortions into the signal.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There is a modification of the HMBC method which suppresses one-bond signals, leaving only the multiple-bond signals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These methods establish correlations between nuclei which are physically close to each other regardless of whether there is a bond between them.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] They use the nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) by which nearby atoms (within about 5 Å) undergo cross relaxation by a mechanism related to spin–lattice relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In NOESY, the nuclear Overhauser cross relaxation between nuclear spins during the mixing period is used to establish the correlations.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The spectrum obtained is similar to COSY, with diagonal peaks and cross peaks, however the cross peaks connect resonances from nuclei that are spatially close rather than those that are through-bond coupled to each other.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NOESY spectra also contain extra *axial peaks* which do not provide extra information and can be eliminated through a different experiment by reversing the phase of the first pulse.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] One application of NOESY is in the study of large biomolecules, such as in protein NMR, in which relationships can often be assigned using sequential walking.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The NOESY experiment can also be performed in a one-dimensional fashion by pre-selecting individual resonances.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The spectra are read with the pre-selected nuclei giving a large, negative signal while neighboring nuclei are identified by weaker, positive signals.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This only reveals which peaks have measurable NOEs to the resonance of interest but takes much less time than the full 2D experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In addition, if a pre-selected nucleus changes environment within the time scale of the experiment, multiple negative signals may be observed.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This offers exchange information similar to the EXSY (exchange spectroscopy) NMR method.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NOESY experiments are important tool to identify stereochemistry of a molecule in solvent whereas single crystal XRD used to identify stereochemistry of a molecule in solid form.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In HOESY, much like NOESY is used for the cross relaxation between nuclear spins.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, HOESY can offer information about other NMR active nuclei in a spatially relevant manner.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The experiments typically observe NOEs from protons on X, X{1H}, but do not have to include protons.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] ROESY is similar to NOESY, except that the initial state is different.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Instead of observing cross relaxation from an initial state of *z*-magnetization, the equilibrium magnetization is rotated onto the *x* axis and then spin-locked by an external magnetic field so that it cannot precess.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In NOESY the cross-relaxation rate constant goes from positive to negative as the correlation time increases, giving a range where it is near zero, whereas in ROESY the cross-relaxation rate constant is always positive.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] ROESY is sometimes called "cross relaxation appropriate for minimolecules emulated by locked spins" (CAMELSPIN).
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Unlike correlated spectra, resolved spectra spread the peaks in a 1D-NMR experiment into two dimensions without adding any extra peaks.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These methods are usually called J-resolved spectroscopy, but are sometimes also known as chemical shift resolved spectroscopy or δ-resolved spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] They are useful for analysing molecules for which the 1D-NMR spectra contain overlapping multiplets as the J-resolved spectrum vertically displaces the multiplet from each nucleus by a different amount.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each peak in the 2D spectrum will have the same horizontal coordinate that it has in a non-decoupled 1D spectrum, but its vertical coordinate will be the chemical shift of the single peak that the nucleus has in a decoupled 1D spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For the heteronuclear version, the simplest pulse sequence used is called a Müller–Kumar–Ernst (MKE) experiment, which has a single 90° pulse for the heteronucleus for the preparation period, no mixing period, and applies a decoupling signal to the proton during the detection period.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There are several variants on this pulse sequence which are more sensitive and more accurate, which fall under the categories of *gated decoupler methods* and *spin-flip methods*.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Homonuclear J-resolved spectroscopy uses the spin echo pulse sequence.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] 3D and 4D experiments can also be done, sometimes by running the pulse sequences from two or three 2D experiments in series.
[src:spectroscopy-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Many of the commonly used 3D experiments, however, are triple resonance experiments; examples include the HNCA and HNCOCA experiments, which are often used in protein NMR.
